The Dallas County HAZMAT team has been designated to provide back-up emergency responders and equipment, and will assume Incident Command upon arrival at the plant. 

PLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY

Based on the hazard reviews and prevention evaluations completed for both ammonia and chlorine, a list of action items was developed and is being considered by Elm Fork WTP management to implement, if feasible.  The most notable planned changes include the following:

7 While the Elm Fork WTP does have a chlorine scrubber, it is not designed to meet the current Uniform Fire Codes.  Therefore, the chlorine scrubber design is planned to be upgraded to meet the current standards.   Also, the establishment of a procedure to routinely test the concentration of the scrubbing solution should be considered.  These tests would ensure that the solution strength is adequate to scrub the contaminated air;

7 Elm Fork WTP management is considering adding remote chlorine sensors and alarms below the rail car spotting site. The consideration of outside leak detection is tied to the periodic need for railcars containing chlorine to be situated outside of the building.  This situation occurs periodically because of the inefficient delivery from the railroad.  Given that extra cars may be spotted outside, the installation of a leak detection system should ensure the detection of any leaks;

7 Ensure that the delivery drivers follow set procedures when delivering either ammonia or chlorine.  MW will coordinate with the staff to develop a procedure to govern the activities of the truck driver or vendor while on plant grounds.  It is anticipated that the vendor can then be subjected to this procedure at the time of the plant's next bid for chemical purchase.  The existing vendor will likely accept these requirements voluntarily to ensure customer satisfaction;

7 Consider the need for automatic kill switches on the

tanks.  These switches would be useful during an emergency if the tanks have to be shut off immediately.  Remote switches also eliminate the danger of plant personnel having to manually shutdown the chlorine and ammonia systems;

7 Consider acquiring emergency response equipment and training for on-site personnel to decrease response times; 

7 Consider exercising the expansion chamber valves in the chlorine and ammonia storage areas periodically.  If this is done, the valves would be exercised regularly and any malfunctions could be detected and repaired before an accident could occur;

7 Evaluate the need to establish a procedure for inspecting and maintaining the rupture disks and tanks in the chlorine and ammonia storage areas.  The current procedure is to replace the equipment as needed.  While this procedure may be adequate, the implementation of a new procedure could help to prevent any major releases; and

7 Consider the need to establish a procedure for routine inspection and maintenance of the ventilation systems.  Currently, only periodic visual inspections of the ductwork are performed at the Elm Fork WTP; however, no set procedure has been established for these inspections.  The implementation of a procedure could help prevent an ineffective use of the scrubber during an emergency.
